content.description: Named after the dog that stood watch the whole time I played around on this awesome slab. Direct standing start anywhere on the slabby section. Sitting to start makes this probably a V2 or harder. No matter where you start, you end in the same place. Mantle the roof to a chill top out and enjoy the view over the Little River.
content.location: West side of the Little South Rock. Obvious slab.

content.description: Stand start on the undercling. Find the hidden right-hand crimp and get a wide stance on the wall. Sail up the lieback and jugs to the top. V-Fun! Don't miss the left hand top-out jug in the crack!
content.location: Left of Freya's Slab. Obvious massive undercling that transitions to a huge lieback.

content.description:
Obvious roof traverse with an up-and-leftward slanting finger jug crack. Get into the bomber finger jugs and traverse up and left until you must top out through the roof corner. The top out is the crux, but the feet are so good and plentiful there is almost no danger of slipping.

Beware of spiders. They love the dark, dry cracks and pockets this face provides. About 40-50 webs were cleaned for the FA attempt.
content.location: Obvious line on the east side of Little South Rock. Squeeze under the tree branches between South Rock and Little South Rock. The route will be directly to your right. Sit start below the end of the crack on the bottom right.
